Introduction¶

I selected Ford GoBike System dataset for analysis, it includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. This data contains 183412 individual rides with 16 features, these features include duration variables such as:duration in sec, start time and end time, also include users information such as:user type and gender.

In this section, we understand the data structure for Ford GoBike System dataset, and make preliminary data wrangling, such as changing data types of variabls, or make sure you don't have too many missing or duplicated values, as following:

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 174952 individual rides in the dataset with 16 features which is duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip. For our datatypes, we have 2 datetime, 4 float, 5 integer and 5 object.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature that interests me from the dataset is the duration of the trip and the factors that can affect it, such as: users age and gender.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe the following features will help me to support my investigation:

  1. start_time.
  2. user_type.
  3. member_birth_year.
  4. member_gender.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, we investigate distributions of individual variables by asking the following questions:

  1. What is distribution of trips duration?
  2. What is distribution of users types?
  3. What is distribution of user gender?
  4. What is distribution of users ages?
  5. What is distribution of trips taken in time of day?
  6. What is distribution of trips taken in days of the week?
  7. What is distribution of bike share for all trip?
  8. What is distribution of start stations and end stations?

I will use ""Question-Visualization-Observations" framework. this framework involves asking a question from the data, creating a visualization to find answers, and then recording observations.

In the following cells I will create a functions to help me :

  1. Customers trip duration take longer than subscribers trip duration.
  2. Female users trip duration take longer than male users trip duration.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  1. On Thursday, the number of customers and subscribers is more than the rest of the week.
  2. Most of customers and subscribers are male.
  3. Most of customers and subscribers they don't share a bike for all trip.
  4. The number of subscribers is more than customers, but the customers take longer trip duration than the subscribers.
  5. The number of males is more than females, but the females take longer trip duration than the males.
  6. The number of trips on Thursday is more than the rest of week, but on Saturday and Sunday, the duration of the trips is longer than the rest of the week.

Conclusions¶

To sum up the previous steps, I started with preliminary wrangling. To understand the Ford GoBike System database, change data types of variabls, and make sure there is no too many missing or duplicated values. Then, I decided to focus on trip duration feature as my feature of interest. I investigate the trip duration feature with multiple other features, whether as a univariante exploriation, bivariate explorations, or multivariate explorations. The following list summarizes the main findings throuhout my investigation:

  1. Distribution of trips duration has right skewed (long talied). So,I used a log transformation on the x-axis, after log transformation most of the trips are between 100 and 2500 seconds with one peak around 650 seconds approximately.
  2. The number of trips increases on Thursday, and the number of trips decreases on Saturday and Sunday.
  3. On Saturday and Sunday, the duration of the trips is longer than the rest of the week.
  4. The users who spend more trip duration are between the ages of 18 and 40.
  5. In general, customer users have a longer trip duration throughout the week than subscriber users.
  6. On Saturday and Sunday, the duration of the trips was longer than the rest of the days of the week for both the subscribers and customers users.
  7. In general, females users have a longer trip duration throughout the week than males users.
  8. On Saturday and Sunday, the duration of the trips was longer than the rest of the days of the week for both the females and males users.
